F. Compatibility With the Underlying Authentication System
In this section, we describe how user authentication fits into full authentication systems. The point of this section is that the choice of authenticator will be influenced by the current computing infrastructure; not all authenticators will be compatible. We describe compatibility with respect to three authentication protocols: Remote Authentication Dial In User Service (RADIUS), Kerberos, and (generic) SSO. The first protocol we describe is RADIUS [33], [34]. Companies, universities, etc., use RADIUS software for managing identities of users needing access to networked computing resources. This protocol involves a shared, centralized authentication server (called the RADIUS server) upon which all users’ authentication data are stored. User
